There is an unspoken truth about creating lead generating content on LinkedIn: 

Eventually, you'll get bored with it. 

I've been thinking about this a lot lately. 

Amateurs write content to entertain themselves. 

Professionals write content that educates their ideal buyers. 

And that means to be successful you must: 

• Write about the same thing 
• Keep making the same points
• Keeping poking at the same pains
• Continue to describe the same outcome 

If you've been writing content consistently, but aren't seeing any results from it, you're probably talking about too many things.

And so your audience: 

• Doesn't understand how you can help
• Is confused about who you are
• Has no clue what you do 

Do yourself a favor and look back through your content over the last 30 days. How many topics are you talking about? 

Are you really positioning yourself as an expert that can help one person achieve one dream outcome? 

You don't want to be saying 1000 different things, but 2-3 things 1000 different ways. 

Do yourself a favor. 

Pick ONE topic and attack it from a bunch of different angles for one month.

I promise you'll start to see progress.

Pick ONE topic and attack it from a bunch of different angles for one month.

I promise you'll start to see progress.

A few years ago, at age 39, I was diagnosed with ADHD. It completely changed my life. 

For my first 38 years, I didn't think it was possible I could have something like ADHD. 

• I did too well in school
• I was too productive at work
• I wasn't hyperactive in any way 

And so, I assumed that the many symptoms I had were signs of my: 

• Laziness
• Disorganization
• Failure as a person 

One big thing made the difference in my light bulb moment, which made me think that maybe, just maybe, there was another explanation.

I started to hear more stories from women with middle-aged diagnoses...

• Women who I looked up to 
• Women whose stories sounded like mine
• Women who achieved so much despite their ADHD

Eventually, I sought out a diagnosis to figure out if this could be an answer for me. And it was. 

My life changed in a few big ways. 

1. I developed more self-compassion 

Understanding WHY I was the way I was made it easier for me to be kind to myself. 

I stopped the internal dialogue of blaming and shaming for my struggles. 

And that helped me step into problem-solving mode. 

2. I learned more practical skills 

I finally stopped assuming my struggles to stay focused and organized were a moral failing, so I began figuring out more practical strategies that could help.

Everything from leveraging tools to help me stay organized to habits and practices to calm my mind. 

3. I got more help 

I stopped assuming I should be able to do it all, accepted that I couldn't (and didn't need to), and started getting more help. 

Everything from hiring a house cleaner at home and using KimKim to plan vacations for Andy and me to bringing Dr. Monica and now some more marketing help into my business.


4. I bonded with people who "got" it 

Over the years, I've learned that a HUGE number of my close friends also have ADHD. 

We understand each other in a way that feels reassuring and supportive.

I'm still learning how to adapt my life to how my brain works, but getting the diagnosis was one of the most loving, kindest things I did for myself. 

It can be scary to accept that your brain or body just works differently from everyone else and you might be thinking "What's the point? I've made it this far." 

But I promise knowing what you're dealing with helps you then figure out what you're gonna do about it.

- About any single decision I have made in my life

- An emotionally abusive marriage and divorce
- Multiple chronic health diagnoses

- Business/career failures

But I didn’t see them as trauma. I saw them as my fault, my foolish mistakes, and my bad luck.

And I thought resilience meant:
- Picking my head up
- Finding the silver lining
- And getting back to work

I never allowed myself to grieve, to process the pain and sadness of my life.

And so it all stayed stored inside of me, manifesting as:

- Chronic health issues
- Deep-seated insecurity
- The ever-present feeling that I was not good enough

It wasn’t until I experienced an absolutely undeniable Trauma that I allowed myself to FEEL the pain that coursed through my veins.

4 years later, I’m still processing it all.

I’ve healed from the dog attack—physically, emotionally, and spiritually—but once I opened the doors to trauma, I was surprised by how much pain came flooding in.

And it’s still really hard to face it all.

- And to create a new vision of life

I have dark angry scars that snake across my arms, but I’m proud as hell of them.

And prouder still of my resilience, my courage, and my continued commitment to healing.

I say all of this as a reminder to myself—of what I’ve been through and how far I’ve come.

7 things nobody tells you about building a stable income as an entrepreneur: 
 
👉 1. The "Niching" Paradox 
 
Niching down is the key to growth.  
 
It helps buyers trust you truly 'get' them.  
 
𝗧𝗶𝗽: Review all past clients to uncover who were:  
 
- The fastest to close 
- The simplest to serve 
- The most fun to work with 
- The easiest to deliver huge results  
 
👉 2. The Automation Myth 
 
Not all automation saves time; choose wisely. 
 
Example: Over-automating social media posts leads to less engagement. 
 
𝗧𝗶𝗽: Automate repetitive tasks but keep personal touches where it matters. 
 
👉 3.

𝗧𝗶𝗽: Automate repetitive tasks but keep personal touches where it matters. 
 
👉 3. The Referral Mirage 
 
Referrals are great, but not a growth strategy. 
 
Relying on them guarantees unstable income.  
 
𝗧𝗶𝗽: Build a personal platform that attracts dream leads outside of your network.  
 
👉 4. The Social Proof Trap 
Quality testimonials beat quantity every time. 
 
Buyers can tell when you're scrounging up B.S. reviews.  
 
𝗧𝗶𝗽: Ask for testimonials that detail the problem you solved and the benefits gained. 
 
👉 5. The Pricing Puzzle 
 
Higher prices often attract more committed clients.

👉 5. The Pricing Puzzle 
 
Higher prices often attract more committed clients. 
 
When your prices are low, buyers view you as less valuable and treat you that way too. 
 
𝗧𝗶𝗽: Review and adjust your pricing strategy to reflect your expertise and the value you deliver. 
 
👉 6. The Work-Life Balance Fantasy 
 
Setting boundaries is the key to true balance. 
 
Taking the time to rest, relax, and recover makes you 10x more impactful the rest of the time.  
 
𝗧𝗶𝗽: Establish clear work-life boundaries and communicate them to clients and colleagues. 
 
👉 7. The Diminishing Returns of Money 
 
The more money you earn, the less it drives you.

👉 7. The Diminishing Returns of Money 
 
The more money you earn, the less it drives you.  
 
Eventually, you realize that income alone isn't the point.  
 
The point is to create the freedom to build a life focused on what (and who) really matter. 
 
𝗧𝗶𝗽: Get clear on why you're really doing this.

But why? 

Those two don't sound like they go together. Because most of the time they don't. 

But I think they should. 

For those of you that don't know, Jocko Willink is a thick-necked Navy SEAL who became famous talking about leadership, discipline, and grit.

Two of his books changed my life and philosophy on the world. 

- Extreme Ownership 
- The Dichotomy of Leadership 

The first is all about taking responsibility. 

- For your circumstances 
- For your results
- For yourself

The second is all about how true leadership is complex and conflicted.

- For your circumstances 
- For your results
- For yourself

The second is all about how true leadership is complex and conflicted. 

- Bold but cautious
- Strong but flexible
- Confident but humble

He was known for: 
- Breaking down racial barriers
- Tackling hard subjects like death & grief
- Emphasizing the specialness of every kid

So how the heck do these two go together?

Anyone who works with me, knows that I will push them to do more. 

- To be disciplined

- To be disciplined

There is only ONE way to get good at something. 

You have to SUCK at it first. 

You can keep trying to strategize and study. 

But you will only grow through action. 

It's time to embrace an Experimental Mindset. 

Your expectations shouldn't be: 

→ To go viral 
→ To write killer content
→ To be immediately kill it online

It's to LEARN.

So think like a scientist. 

What is one hypothesis you want to test? 

Maybe it's a topic to write about. 
Or the type of post to write. 
Or the person to write for. 

Pick one. 

Then identify two options for it. 

And write 2-3 posts for each option. 

Post them all and see what you learn. 

→ How did it feel to write them? 
Did it energize or drain? 
Was it easy or a slog? 

→ How did people respond to the posts? 
Did your ideal audience respond? 
Did they engage or ignore? 

Be a beginner again! 

Low standards are liberating. And fun. 

And you'll get good a LOT faster this way. 

I promise.

→ To delivering the highest quality work
→ To being present with my husband
→ To my work-life balance
→ To managing my stress 
→ To my physical health

→ The activities I won't continue
→ The types of clients I won't serve
→ The kinds of projects I won't take on

Offers, clients, growth strategies...

But you will be best served by removing instead.
